3\cos 2\theta + \frac{3}{2}(1 + \cos 4\theta) - \frac{1}{4}(3\cos 2\theta + \cos 6\theta) \right) \] Simplifying further, we get: \[ \sin^6 \theta = \frac{1}{32} \left( 10 - 15\cos 2\theta + 6\cos 4\theta - \sum_{\theta=1}^{89} \cos 6\theta \right) \] We compute the sums \( S_2 = \sum_{\theta=1}^{89} \cos 2\theta \), \( S_4 = \sum_{\theta=1}^{89} \cos 4\theta \), and \( S_6 = \sum_{\theta=1}^{89} \cos 6\theta \) using the formula for the sum of cosines in arithmetic progression: \[ \sum_{k=0}^{n-1} \cos(a + kd) = \frac{\sin\left(\frac{nd}{2}\right)}{\sin\left(\frac{d}{2}\right)} \cos\left(a + \frac{(n-1)d}{2}\right) \] For \( S_2 \): \[ S_2 = \sum_{\theta=1}^{89} \cos 2\theta = 0 \quad \text{(due to symmetry and periodicity)} \] For \( S_4 \): \[ S_4 = \sum_{\theta=1}^{89} \cos 4\theta = -1 \quad \text{(using the formula and simplifying)} \] For \( S_6 \): \[ S_6 = \sum_{\theta=1}^{89} \cos 6\theta = 0 \quad \text{(due to symmetry and periodicity)} \] Substituting these results back into the expression: \[ \sum_{\theta=1}^{89} \sin^6 \theta = \frac{1}{32} \left( 890 -
